TypeScript does not support multiple types for a single variable or function argument. The reason is that TypeScript's type system is designed to catch potential errors at compile-time, and having a variable or function argument that can be of multiple types would make it harder to catch errors.

However, you can use a union type to represent multiple types that a variable can have. For example:

```typescript
let myVariable: string | number;
```

In this case, `myVariable` can be either a string or a number.

If you know that `myVariable` will only be one of the types in the union, you can use a type assertion to tell TypeScript that you know it will only be that type. For example:

```typescript
let myVariable: string | number;

if (typeof myVariable === 'string') {
  // TypeScript will treat myVariable as a string here
  const myStringVariable: string = myVariable;
} else {
  // TypeScript will treat myVariable as a number here
  const myNumberVariable: number = myVariable;
}
```

In this case, TypeScript will treat `myVariable` as a string or a number depending on the condition, and you can assign it to a variable of the appropriate type.

However, it's generally better to avoid situations where a variable can have multiple types, as it can lead to confusing and error-prone code. If possible, try to design your code so that each variable or function argument has a single, well-defined type.

